{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504329","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504329"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:14:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:14:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2321"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2321","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2321"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.02,0.12,0.68,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2321"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"30445"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2321","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2321"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2321"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"16387"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"540"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1028"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1029"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"30445","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/30445"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 59-year-old man presents with a one week history of fever, chills and left sided abdominal pain. His medical history includes hypertension and ischaemic heart disease. He takes perindopril and four weeks ago had a pacemaker inserted for heart block. He has a 30 pack-year smoking history and quit five years ago. He drinks two cans of beer a day and works on a local sheep station. On examination his blood pressure is 110/70 mmHg, pulse 90/min and temperature 38.4C. His abdomen is soft, apart from some tenderness in the left upper quadrant. A CT scan is performed (Image 1, 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hydatid cyst","Gastrointestinal stromal tumour","Haematoma of the spleen","Splenic abscess","Diverticular abscess"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe CT scan shows a well-defined spherical mass within the spleen. It is homogenous and thin-walled, measuring some 8 x 12 cm. From its appearance and the clinical history, this is most likely to be a \u003Cstrong\u003Esplenic abscess\u003C/strong\u003E. The patient has febrile illness and has recently had device implanted which could be infected, leading to infective endocarditis. A haematoma of this size would be less likely to have a homogeneous consistency. An hydatid cyst is a possible (radiological) diagnosis, but the history would not support this. At one time hydatid disease was endemic in the sheep-rearing regions of Australia, but has now been virtually eradicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESplenic abscess formation is uncommon and if not recognised, is associated with a high mortality rate. The source of infection is often haematogenous in origin, with infective endocarditis being the most frequent cause.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Abscess formation is a well recognised complication of infective endocarditis."],"references":["Lee M-C, Lee C-M. Splenic Abscess: An Uncommon Entity with Potentially\nLife-Threatening Evolution. Canadian J Infect Dis Med Micro 2018; 8610657"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"16387"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2321"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18395"},{"type":"media","id":"18396"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18395","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18395"},"attributes":{"mim